\section{Reviewer \#2}
\addtocounter{section}{-2}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% Comment %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\rcomment{
Dear authors,
Thank you for submitting your paper to the Energies. I think your paper is an informative paper that can be published after a major revision.

\vspace{0.5cm}
It is not clear what the research gap that the paper is addressing. What is the objective of this paper? Please clarify somewhere clearly all your contributions.
}

\textbf{Response:}
{
First of all, we would like to thank Reviewer \#2 for his/her suggestions to improve the paper.

The reviewer is right about this comment, we have not adequately indicated what the purpose of this work is. We think that this work can be useful as a support for applications in fields of marine energy and engineering and environment, by creating datasets well-formed and ready to be used with ML and SC prediction techniques. Datasets can be used both in classification and regression problems from the integration of NDBC observations and NNRP reanalysis data.

In our understanding, manuscripts in marine energy and engineering that use ML and SC algorithms for prediction tasks, do not provide tools for incorporating and integrating the two data sources used by SPAMDA and considering the casuistry involved. These studies apply specific algorithms (extreme learning machine, metaheuristics, Bayesian networks, artificial neural networks, etc) on data, using own implementations or scripts developed in some programming language, but they do not allow to build  datasets ready to be used with any of those methodologies or algorithms by an automated and very versatile process. In this sense, it is convenient to indicate that, therefore, the objectives of these types of works and our contributions are different. Although this software allows the use of ML and SC algorithms available in WEKA (datasets can be also created in .csv format to researchers can use other tools appart from WEKA), we do not focus on those methodologies nor on improving them.

Some of these clarifications are expressed in \textbf{Section ``1. Introduction" (lines 112-129)}, and others have been added in \textbf{''Abstract`` (lines 10-19)} and \textbf{Section ``5. Conclusions`` (lines 759-769)}, so that the reader can better understand the scope of our work. \textbf{Comments 4 and 9} suggested by Reviewer \#2 are also related to these clarifications included in \textbf{''Abstract``} and \textbf{Section ''5. Conclusions''}.

%\textcolor{blue}{So that the reader can better understand the scope of this work, it is necessary to indicate that this work does not focus on carrying out extensive experimentation and validation of results, together with statistical tests to check if significant differences exist between different prediction methodologies. We do not focus on the ML and SC methodologies and the comparisons used by the researcher, we provide an automated and versatile process that builds a data integration of NDBC and NNRP well-formatted and with the possibility of multiple configurations. It, along with another series of functionalities related to this integration and that are explained in depth throughout the manuscript.}

At the end of \textbf{Section ``1. Introduction'', (lines 133-171)}, we have tried to summarize in a general way the contributions of SPAMDA, which are specified and detailed throughout the paper. Below, we comment on some contributions that have also been taken into account in this revised version of the manuscript (\textbf{highlighted in blue color}):
\begin{itemize}
	
	\item SPAMDA allows preliminary studies of missing values (dates or measurements not recorded) in buoys managed by NDBC, so that researchers have an idea of the quality of data observed by buoys and whether these would be suitable for the work to be carried out. Sometimes, buoys do not collect observations temporarily due to mechanical problems or weather conditions, so depending on the problem to be solved, such raw data could not be appropriate for accurate modelling. Even so, SPAMDA allows data integration taking into account such missing values when needed by researchers. More details about how this task is performed can be found in \textbf{Section ``2. Meteorological data sources'', lines 212-219 (``Note ...Appendix A.''), Section ``3.2. Datasets'', lines 287-290 (``When ...dates.''), Section ``3.3. Pre-process'', lines 319-332 (``Recover ...values mean.''), Section ``3.4. Matching configuration'', lines 402-407 (``Include ...as \guillemotleft\textit{?}\guillemotright''), and Section ``Appendix A. Managing the casuistry of incomplete data''}.

	\item Although pre-processing is not the main objective of SPAMDA, the tool also provides some basic pre-processing filters on buoys measurements, such as normalisation and missing data recovery (more details about it in \textbf{Section ``3.3. Pre-process'', lines 327-332 (``Replace ...values mean'')}).
	
	\item Building of different configurations of datasets with little effort and in an automated process, either regarding the input variables from the NNRP (in the original .nc format are unreadable) or the output variable to be used in prediction tasks using NDBC data, both for classification and for regression (more details about it in \textbf{Section ``3.4. Matching configuration'' and Section ''3.5. Final datasets``}).
	
	\item The possibility of using, also in an automated process, several reanalysis nodes near to the NDBC buoy under study, so that a greater amount of information is available, which could provide more accurate models (more details about it in \textbf{Section ''3.4. Matching configuration``, lines 408-421 (''Nearest ...respectively``)}).
	
	\item Estimation of the amount of energy flux that can be produced at different prediction horizons, for example, what approximate amount of energy could bet obtained in 6 hours, 12 hours, 18 hours, 24 hours, ... It should be taken into account that with a greater prediction horizon the models tend to generalise worse, but that is something we do not focus on either, it is a decision of the researcher (more details in \textbf{Section ''3.5. Final datasets``, lines 467-506 (''Prediction ...(${t+\Delta t}$ in Eq. 5)``)}.	

	\item This software would be provided to the scientific community as a free and open source tool, so that any researcher could access its source code and extend its functionality (the github repository is show in \textbf{Section "Additional material"}).
\end{itemize}

From an applicability point of view, SPAMDA could be used in ocean engineering applications, and applications related to marine energy and prediction, such as:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Estimate the need for other energy sources in hybrid energy systems, based on the amount of energy that can be obtained by a marine energy system in the next 6 hours or 12 hours for example.
    
    \item Regulation of WECs to avoid malfunction or breakage, depending on the significant wave height and/or energy flux expected, as well as the possibility of reconfiguring them in order to maximise the wave energy extraction.
        
    \item Decision-making in exploitation and environmental protection for the construction of marine energy storage plants, future strategies on renewable energy and coastal planning.
    
    \item Support for the prediction of the energy that could be obtained from a certain maritime location, so that it is possible to know whether or not it is convenient to install WECS in marine structures such as offshore oil and gas platforms or seawater desalination plants.
        
    \item Design of offshore structures and ports.
    
    \item Decision-making and risk assessment about operational works in the sea, security systems for structures or naval security.
\end{itemize}

Some of these clarifications about applicability have been written in \textbf{Section ''1. Introduction``, lines 172-186.} 
}
