\textbf{Response:}
{
Thank you very much to the reviewer for questioning this fact and allow us to clarify it.

Although we have cited some software tools related to energy prediction and environmental modelling, as well as works that use ML and SC methodologies in marine energy studies (now much more complete with the references provided by the Reviewer \#2 in \textbf{Comment 7}), we have not carried out an exhaustive review of the state-of-the-art because, to our knowledge, there are no open source software tools available to the scientific community, that perform the data integration provided by SPAMDA with the functionalities described in this work. 

The reading order of the contents shown in \textbf{Section "1. Introduction"}, has been carried out with the intention that is commented below, and the background has been reinforced with the interesting references suggested by the Reviewer \#2 (\textbf{Section ''1. Introduction, lines 37-39, 66, 74, 80-81, 86-94}):
\begin{enumerate}
    \item First, the reader is introduced to the importance of having quality and well-formed meteorological data and observations concerning studies of environmental comprehension, conservation, modelling and prediction, providing examples of this. It is also indicated that ML and SC methodologies, despite managing uncertainty, need adequate data for the creation of good models. \textbf{Lines 23-43 (``A better ...models.'')}.
       
    \item Continuing in that line, in second place it is indicated that researchers need special-purpose software to be able to perform data adaptation tasks and to carry out studies related to energy and environmental modelling. \textbf{Lines 44-59 (``Continuing ...traker'')}.
    
    \item Thirdly, marine energy is introduced as one of the most widely used renewable and sustainable energy sources today, where meteorological data is used for prediction purposes. Wecs are also introduced as the main mechanical devices for capturing and converting energy from waves and tides. It is concluded that both for the correct design and use of WECS and for other applications related to marine energy, it is very useful to have adequate prediction models, for which it is necessary to have both data and techniques that use them. \textbf{Lines 60-77 (``Marine ...\textit{wave energy period} ($T_e$).'')}.
    
    \item Fourthly, it is commented how current ML and SC methodologies are supporting traditional statistical modelling procedures and that there are tools such as Weka that can be used even by researchers who are not specialized in the field of artificial intelligence or in the use of programming languages.  Also included are examples of work using ML algorithms for wave height and energy flow prediction in relation to marine energy. In this part, it is emphasized that both for these tools that offer a user-friendly environment for researchers not specialized in ML and for more specific work, the data is essential and is usually not in the right format. This causes them to have shortcomings and inconsistencies that prevent their treatment, so a great deal of effort and time is spent on resolving them. \textbf{Lines 78-111 (``Currently ...tedious task.'')}.  
    
    \item Next, it is indicated that the main purpose of this work is to solve in an automatic, versatile and simple way, the integration of observations from NDBC and reanalysis data from NNRP, without focusing on the ML and SC methodologies that use them. For it, a software tool has been developed that takes into account the casuistry involved in this data integration for marine energy prediction tasks. \textbf{Lines 112-129 (``The main ...tools'')}.
        
    \item Finally, the functionalities and the general contributions of the developed tool are indicated, as well as some examples of applicability. \textbf{Lines 130-171 (``In order to ...system''), 172-186 (``Therefore, ...planning'')} .The following sections of the manuscript explain in detail the contributions of SPAMDA and how they are carried out, ending with a case study in the Gulf of Alaska about significant wave height and energy flux prediction.
\end{enumerate}
}
