\textbf{Response:}
{
First of all, we would like to thank Reviewer \#3 for his/her suggestions.

We had not adequately indicated what the purpose of this work is in the initial version, we hope that it is now better clarified. So that the reader can better understand the scope of this work, it is necessary to indicate that this work does not focus on carrying out extensive experimentation and validation of results, together with statistical tests to check if significant differences exist between different prediction methodologies. We do not focus on the ML and SC methodologies and the comparisons used by the researcher, we provide an automated and versatile process that builds a data integration of NDBC and NNRP well-formatted and with the possibility of multiple configurations, along with another series of functionalities related to this integration and that are explained in depth throughout the manuscript.

In this revised version of the manuscript we have tried to clarify the contributions of this work, emphasizing it mainly in \textbf{Abstract, lines 10-19, Section “1. Introduction”, lines 133-171, 172-186 and Section “5. Conclusions“, lines 759-769.} Another place in the paper where the possibility of using this tool in relation to the WECS is discussed is found in \textbf{''Section “1. Introduction”, lines 60-77}. 

In our opinion, we think that this work can be useful and support applications in the field of energy and the environment, and in energy saving, production and conversion processes. Prediction works using ML and SC algorithms do not provide a simple tool to incorporate and integrate the two data sources used by SPAMDA and the casuistry that this entails. These studies apply specific algorithms (extreme learning machine, metaheuristics, Bayesian networks, artificial neural networks, etc) on specific data, from own implementations or scripts made with some programming language, but they do not allow to build datasets ready to be used with any of those methodologies or algorithms by an automated and versatile process.

We think that this software tool can be used in coastal and ocean engineering applications, and applications related to marine energy and prediction, such as:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Estimate the need for other energy sources in hybrid energy systems, based on the amount of energy that can be obtained by a marine energy system in the next 6 hours or 12 hours for example.
    
    \item Regulation of WECs to avoid malfunction or breakage, depending on the significant wave height and/or energy flux expected, as well as the possibility of reconfiguring them in order to maximise the wave energy extraction.
        
    \item Decision-making in exploitation and environmental protection for the construction of marine energy storage plants, future strategies on renewable energy and coastal planning.
    
    \item Support for the prediction of the energy that could be obtained from a certain maritime location, so that it is possible to know whether or not it is convenient to install WECS in marine structures such as offshore oil and gas platforms or seawater desalination plants.
        
    \item Design of offshore structures and ports.
    
    \item Decision-making and risk assessment about operational works in the sea, security systems for structures or naval security.
\end{itemize}

Finally, to try to clarify more that this application can be used in the field of marine energy, \textbf{we have extended the case study} carried out in the Gulf of Alaska with a \textbf{short-term forecasting of energy flux} generated by the waves of the location used. In this way, it would be possible to predict 6 hours in advance (configurable prediction horizon), how much energy could be obtained with the use of WECs. The Reviewer \#3 can view this extension in the \textbf{red lines and new figures in Section ''4. A case study applied to Gulf of Alaska``. Some lines (red lines) in Sections ''3.4. Matching configuration`` and ''3.5. Final datasets`` also had to be rewritten for this purpose, as well as unifying several figures}.

